The murder of Dutch filmmaker Theo van Gogh sparked outrage and fears of ethnic tensions in the Netherlands.
Van Gogh, known for his controversial views on Islam, was shot and stabbed to death while cycling in Amsterdam.
Despite his provocative nature, many condemned the attack as an assault on freedom of speech.
The suspect, with ties to Islamic extremists, left a letter advocating for a religious war.
Dutch society mourned his death, with Muslim groups denouncing the killing and calling for reconciliation.
The tragic event highlighted the delicate balance between free expression and security in a diverse society.
